      "title": "Module 2: The recovery protocol",
      "text": "So if a slip ever happens, here is exactly what to do — decided now, while calm:\n\n• Stop immediately. Put it out. Don't finish it, and certainly don't have another. The damage of one is tiny and recoverable; the danger is in the second.\n\n• Refuse the catastrophe. Catch the \"I've ruined it\" thought and reject it out loud: \"That was one mistake, not a verdict. I am not a smoker again. One slip does not erase three weeks of freedom.\"\n\n• Get curious, not ashamed. Treat it as data: what situation, what state, what thought led here? You've just learned exactly where your plan needs reinforcing.\n\n• Re-commit, same day. Don't wait for Monday or \"a fresh start.\" Renew your decision in the next hour: \"I have smoked my last cigarette. Again. Still a non-smoker.\"\n\n• Patch the plan. Update your high-risk playbook so that specific situation has a stronger response next time.\n\nNotice what's missing from that list: shame spirals, \"starting over from zero,\" and writing yourself off. None of those help; all of them increase relapse risk. Self-compassion after a slip isn't going soft — it's the protective move. People who treat a lapse kindly and correct course recover; people who beat themselves up tend to keep smoking to escape the shame."
